stulation with physical understanding is difﬁcult. This capability of a FFNN to model highly nonlinear complex phenomena and handle the process noise [3] in a better way has been used to estimate the aerodynamic parameters from ﬂight data at high angles of attack. It has also been shown [3] during the modeling of lift, drag, and pitching moment coefﬁcients of the research aircraft HFB-320 that the predictive capability of the trained FFNN for ﬂight data with atmospheric turbulence is found to be good. Neural Gauss–Newton (NGN) method, proposed by Peyada and Ghosh [8], is an algorithm that uses FFNN and the Gauss–Newton optimization method to estimate aerodynamic parameters fromﬂight data. The NGN method does not require solving of equations of motion. The functional relationship between the input and output variables is mapped implicitly using FFNN. Because of non-availability of the aerodynamicmodel near stall, it was decided to use NGN method to capture aerodynamic model using ﬂight data near stall. The ﬂight data (near stall) were generated using in-house research aircraft Hansa-3. Both the Maximum Likelihood (ML) and the NGN methods have been used for this study. This Technical Note evaluates the suitability/adequacy of the nonlinear aerodynamic model for stall aerodynamics [3] for the purpose of extraction of aerodynamic parameters. The study showed that the NGN method can advantageously be applied on ﬂight data to capture nonlinear aerodynamics (near stall).},
